This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it proposes a novel head inpainting technique for obfuscating identities in personal photos. The paper also mentions the use of facial landmark generation and facial landmark conditioned head inpainting, which are common techniques in computer vision. 

The paper may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category as it deals with personal photos and their privacy protection. 

The graphics (cs.GR) sub-category is also a possibility as the paper involves generating realistic person images. 

The human-computer interaction (cs.HC) sub-category is another possibility as the paper discusses the user experience of current obfuscation techniques. 

Lastly, the cryptography and security (cs.CR) sub-category may also be relevant as the paper deals with privacy protection in personal photos.
